  Post and telecommunications undertakings developed rapidly. 
Total post and telecommunications business volume fulfilled in 
the whole year amounted to 102.62 million yuan, an increase of 
53.4 percent over the previous year, of which were manifold 
increases in the business of express delivery, wireless paging, 
and mobile telephones. The total number of city telephones 
reached 91,163, an increase of 39 percent; and 
program-controlled telephones in the whole region reached 
59,562, an increase of 36,100 telephones over the previous year, 
up 1.5 times. 
<H5>  V. Domestic and Foreign Trade and Market Prices </H5>
  Urban and rural markets were brisk, with an ample supply of 
commodities. In 1993 the total amount of social commodity 
retail sales in the whole region was 4.3 billion yuan, an 
increase of 15.4 percent over the previous year, of which 
consumer goods retail sales amounted to 3.77 billion yuan, an 
increase of 18.8 percent. In consumer goods retail sales, sales 
to residents amounted to 3.36 billion yuan, up 19.9 percent. 
Divided by urban and rural areas, sales in cities amounted to 
2.25 billion yuan, up 19.1 percent; sales at the county level 
amounted to one billion yuan, up 20 percent; and sales below the 
county level amounted to 520 million yuan, up 15.2 percent. 
  There was overall growth in commodity retail sales of 
various 
economic types. State-owned business retail sales in 1993 
amounted to two billion yuan, an increase of 12.1 percent over 
the previous year, accounting for 46.5 percent of total retail 
sales; collective business retail sales amounted to 960 million 
yuan, an increase of 0.9 percent; individual business retail 
sales amounted to 730 million yuan, an increases of 31.5 
percent; country fair trade was extremely brisk, and the sales 
of wares by peasants to nonpeasants amounted to 600 million 
yuan, up 39.5 percent. The growth in the sales of various major 
consumer goods was: Grain grew by 10.5 percent, eggs by two 
times, aquatic products by 38.5 percent, various kinds clothing 
by 75.3 percent, TV sets by 14 percent, and refrigerators by 
37.1 percent. 
  In the first half of the year there was tension between 
supply and demand in the market of the means of production, and 
prices went up. In the second half of the year, the market 
turned brisk, with an ample supply of goods, and prices went 
down. Annual sales of the agricultural means of production 
dropped by 4 percent from those of the previous year. 
  Foreign trade developed further. In 1993, the total foreign 
import and export value in the whole region amounted to 143.50 
million dollars, an increase of 14.2 percent, of which export 
amounted to 111.24 million dollars, down 1.1 percent, and import 
amounted to 32.26 million dollars, an increase of 99 percent. 
Export commodities increased to 140 varieties. The annual 
export volume of foreign-funded enterprises amounted to 5.51 
million dollars, up 1.1 times. 
  The use of foreign investment increased by a big margin. In 
1993 the actual use of foreign investment amounted to 36.66 
million dollars, an increase of 2.6 times over 1992. Contracts 
for 181 projects were newly signed for foreign-funded 
enterprises, an increase of 118 percent, and actual use of 
foreign investments in these contracts amounted to 11.90 million 
dollars, an increase of 2.4 times. At the end of the year, 
there were 261 foreign-funded enterprises, an increase of 187 
percent. 
  In 1993, visitors coming to Ningxia from overseas and from 
Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan totalled 2,905 person trips, and 
foreign exchange income from tourism amounted to 3.75 million 
yuan, an increase of 14 percent over the previous year. 
  Pricing reforms made bigger strides forward, and there were 
big increases in market prices. Under the nationwide unified 
arrangement, a number of pricing reforms were introduced in a 
planned way. Prices of grain and other important commodities 
were released; and rent and the prices of service items, 
electric power, fuel, and other living expenses were raised. 
The extent of marketization of the economy as a whole was 
enhanced, and the proportion of market regulation increased. 
However, due to incomplete complementary measures for pricing 
reforms, market prices rose rapidly, the overall price level was 
obviously too high, and the price scissors between industrial 
products and agricultural products further widened. 


